The paper deals with algorithmic techniques and approximation algorithms for a well-studied problem in computer science, the unsplittable flow problem on a path. This problem is related to resource allocation, bandwidth allocation, and scheduling, which are all topics in the area of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also introduces novel algorithmic techniques, which could be of independent interest, and uses dynamic programming and geometric insights to solve the problem, which are topics in graph theory (cs.GT), discrete mathematics (cs.DM), and algorithms (cs.AL). The paper also discusses the complexity of the problem and shows that it is strongly NP-hard, which is a topic in computational complexity (cs.CC).
